Electricity supplier
Farming and forestry
Skyllbergs Bruk provides electricity to roughly 1,400 subscribers. The electricity distribution network has been expanded successively since the beginning of the 1900s. Originally, the electricity was produced by the company‚Äôs four hydroelectric power stations to satisfy its own electricity demand.
Well-managed forests have long been a consuming passion at Skyllbergs Bruk. The most common species of tree in the surrounding forests are spruce, pine and birch. The area of the working agricultural and forestry land exceeds 1,600 hectares. There is an abundance of moose roaming the woods and moose hunting, conducted during the last two weeks of October, is a favourite pastime for many of the local residents. Customers are also frequently invited to take part in moose hunting.
Housing
Subsidiaries around Sweden
Skyllbergs Bruk has rented houses to company employees for far more than a hundred years. The oldest buildings were raised in 1795 and for many years were the homes of the company‚Äôs tilt hammer smiths and their families. Nowadays, the company owns about 65 apartments, single-family houses and holiday cottages situated in Skyllberg and K√•rberg.
One of the company‚Äôs subsidiaries, Nils Ahlgren AB, is a wholesale supplier to hardware stores and building supply companies around Sweden. This Stockholm-based company has been in Skyllberg‚Äôs hands since 1982. The products handled by Nils Ahlgren include nails and screws, fittings, net and fencing products.
Degerfors, a village about 70 kilometres from Skyllberg, is the site of the hot dip galvanizing company Defab (Degerfors F√∂rzinknings AB) which has been a member of the Skyllberg Group since 1996. Steel structures up to 18 metres in length can be dipped in molten zinc (460 degrees C) to provide a surface finish that withstands corrosion.
